pr_review_comment_body:
@scottpurdy, regarding
> Was this file missing the close for a multiline comment? I don't see an opening added

No, nothing changed in that regard. When I made other changes in this file, the editor removed trailing spaces, which is what you're seeing on this line.

Can you try to make simpler test data and remove duplicated code from two tests?

```python
def test_continue_run_multiple_conflicts_per_path(self):
    lca = {'first': [1, 2]}
    first = {'first': [1, 2, 3]}
    second = {'second': 2}
    expected = [
        ('f', {'first': [1, 2, 3], 'second': 2}),
        ('s', {'second': 2}),
    ]

    for resolution, result in expected:
        m = Merger(lca, first, second, {})
       try:
           m.run()
        except UnresolvedConflictsException as e:
           m.continue_run([status for _ in e.content])

        self.assertEqual(patch(m.unified_patches, lca), result)
```

I just generally always use classmethods instead of staticmethods to allow for future subclassing/testing.  For example, we could write an implementation like so:

```python
class BuggyResolvableSet(_ResolvableSet):
  @classmethod
  def normalize(cls, name):
    return name
```

and then assert that it fails when running the same test suite as the regular implementation.

As it stands, we're subclassing it nowhere and it's an internal class so it doesn't really give us any leverage over a staticmethod but why be inconsistent.

IMO, a stream is a general term for a set of events that happen through time. In can be used in computational contexts that don't relate to reactive programming at all. An Observable is a wrapper around a stream that gives you additional functionality like merging and filtering. In our specific case, we are returning streams in the form of Observables in all our code so you need to write.
```
@param {Rx.Observable} setInputStream 
```

@rgbkrk might have better ideas since he works with RxJS all day.

```python
if isinstance(batch_apis, (six.text_type, six.binary_type)):
```
